The Hong Kong Protests: A Twitter Story

Raising public awareness about China-backed information operations campaigns on Twitter

Twitter tracks and publishes datasets from alleged foreign influence campaigns in the spirit of serving the public conversation.

This dashboard aims to make the data accessible to the public to demonstrate examples of disinformation campaigns happening on social media today.

Overview

Date range: 2007-12-23 to 2019-08-28

Total number of tweets: 13847731

Number of distinct tweeters: 5191

Number of distinct hashtags: 302739

Number of distinct languages tweeted in: 64

Background

In August 2019, Twitter disclosed the existence of significant state-backed information operations around the Hong Kong protests, including accounts coordinating to undermine the legitimacy and political positions of the protest movement on the ground. Their investigation suggests that this is a coordinated state-backed operation.

The accounts in this dataset have been identified by Twitter as relating to China-backed disinformation campaigns. The datasets used in this dashboard are the three China-related dataset disclosures from August & September 2019.

Tweets from accounts connected to state-backed information operations

Mapping User-reported Locations

Users are allowed to self-report their location. According to this data, tweets come from all over the world, but many claim to be in the United States. There are 498 distinct locations listed.

The Australian Strategic Policy Institute has hypothesized that these locations likely reflect the former nature of the accounts as spam and marketing bots.

Notes

Why are some usernames nonsensical?

According to Twitter, accounts with fewer than 5,000 followers had identifying fields hashed (i.e. user ID and screen name).

Why are the retweet numbers different than what I'm seeing in the raw data?

Retweets and quoted tweets have combined in this dasbboard for the purpose of counting retweet engagement.

What inspired this work?

This dashboard was inspired by the Hamilton 2.0 dashboard by the Alliance for Securing Democracy.

Where can I read more about this misinformation campaign?

The Australian Strategic Policy Initiative has conducted similar analysis. Quartz has conducted a deep dive into the history of these accounts prior to the Hong Kong-focused misinformation campaign.
